# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tower-middleware
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] In computer programming, the **async/await pattern** is a syntactic feature of many programming languages that allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] The feature is found in C#, C++, Python, F#, Hack, Julia, Dart, Kotlin, Rust, Nim, JavaScript, and Swift.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] F# added asynchronous workflows with await points in version 2.0 in 2007.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] This influenced the async/await mechanism added to C#.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Haskell lead developer Simon Marlow created the async package in 2010.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Microsoft first released a version of C# with async/await in the Async CTP (2011).
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] It was later officially released in C# 5 (2012).
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Python added support for async/await with version 3.5 in 2015 adding 2 new keywords, `async` and `await`.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] TypeScript added support for async/await with version 1.7 in 2015.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] JavaScript added support for async/await in 2017 as part of ECMAScript 2017 JavaScript edition.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Rust added support for async/await with version 1.39.0 in 2019 using the `async` keyword and the `.await` postfix operator, both introduced in the 2018 edition of the language.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] C++ added support for async/await with version 20 in 2020 with 3 new keywords `co_return`, `co_await`, `co_yield`.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Swift added support for async/await with version 5.5 in 2021, adding 2 new keywords `async` and `await`.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] This was released alongside a concrete implementation of the Actor model with the `actor` keyword which uses async/await to mediate access to each actor from outside.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] A function using async/await can use as many `await` expressions as it wants, and each will be handled in the same way (though a promise will only be returned to the caller for the first await, while every other await will utilize internal callbacks).
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] A function can also hold a promise object directly and do other processing first (including starting other asynchronous tasks), delaying awaiting the promise until its result is needed.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Functions with promises also have promise aggregation methods that allow the program to await multiple promises at once or in some special pattern (such as C#'s `Task.WhenAll()`, which returns a valueless `Task` that resolves when all of the tasks in the arguments have resolved).
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Many promise types also have additional features beyond what the async/await pattern normally uses, such as being able to set up more than one result callback or inspect the progress of an especially long-running task.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] In the particular case of C#, and in many other languages with this language feature, the async/await pattern is not a core part of the language's runtime, but is instead implemented with lambdas or continuations at compile time.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Because of this, if an interface method needs to return a promise object, but itself does not require `await` in the body to wait on any asynchronous tasks, it does not need the `async` modifier either and can instead return a promise object directly.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] For instance, a function might be able to provide a promise that immediately resolves to some result value (such as C#'s `Task.FromResult()`), or it may simply return another method's promise that happens to be the exact promise needed (such as when deferring to an overload).
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] One important caveat of this functionality, however, is that while the code resembles traditional blocking code, the code is actually non-blocking and potentially multithreaded, meaning that many intervening events may occur while waiting for the promise targeted by an `await` to resolve.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] The C language does not support await/async.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Some coroutine libraries such as *s_task* simulate the keywords await/async with macros.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] In C++, await (named `co_await` in C++ to emphasise its context in coroutines) has been officially merged into C++20.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Support for it, coroutines, and the keywords such as `co_await` are available in GCC and MSVC compilers while Clang has partial support.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] A proper task class, `std::execution::task`, was introduced in C++26.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] To call it, use `std::execution::sync_wait()`, which returns `std::optional<std::tuple<Ts...>>`.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] It is worth noting that `std::promise` and `std::future`, although it would seem that they would be awaitable objects, implement none of the machinery required to be returned from coroutines and be awaited using `co_await`.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Programmers must implement a number of public member functions, such as `await_ready`, `await_suspend`, and `await_resume` on the return type in order for the type to be awaited on.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] In 2012, C# added the async/await pattern in C# with version 5.0, which Microsoft refers to as the task-based asynchronous pattern (TAP).
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Async methods usually return either `void`, `Task`, `Task<T>`, `ValueTask` or `ValueTask<T>`.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] User code can define custom types that async methods can return through custom *async method builders* but this is an advanced and rare scenario.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Async methods that return `void` are intended for event handlers; in most cases where a synchronous method would return `void`, returning `Task` instead is recommended, as it allows for more intuitive exception handling (note that `Task<void>` is invalid in C#).
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Methods that make use of `await` must be declared with the `async` keyword.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] In methods that have a return value of type `Task<T>`, methods declared with `async` must have a return statement of type assignable to `T` instead of `Task<T>`; the compiler wraps the value in the `Task<T>` generic.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] It is also possible to `await` methods that have a return type of `Task` or `Task<T>` that are declared without `async`.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] The following async method downloads data from a URL using `await`.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Because this method issues a task for each URI before requiring completion with the `await` keyword, the resources can load at the same time instead of waiting for the last resource to finish before starting to load the next.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] In 2007, F# added asynchronous workflows with version 2.0.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] The asynchronous workflows are implemented as CE (computation expressions).
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] They can be defined without specifying any special context (like `async` in C#).
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] F# asynchronous workflows append a bang (!) to keywords to start asynchronous tasks.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Java does not have `async` and `await` keywords in the language, however it can be emulated using the `java.util.concurrent` package, such as the class `CompletableFuture` (introduced in Java 8).
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Asynchronous programming is later improved in Java 21 with the introduction of virtual threads and structured task scopes.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] The await operator in JavaScript (and TypeScript) can only be used from inside an async function or at the top level of a module.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] If the parameter is a promise, execution of the async function will resume when the promise is resolved (unless the promise is rejected, in which case an error will be thrown that can be handled with normal JavaScript exception handling).
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] If the parameter is not a promise, the parameter itself will be returned immediately.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Many libraries provide promise objects that can also be used with await, as long as they match the specification for native JavaScript promises.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] However, promises from the jQuery library were not Promises/A+ compatible until jQuery 3.0.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Node.js version 8 includes a utility that enables using the standard library callback-based methods as promises.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] The Future::AsyncAwait module was the subject of a Perl Foundation grant in September 2018.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Python 3.5 (2015) has added support for async/await as described in PEP 492 (written and implemented by Yury Selivanov).
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] On November 7, 2019, async/await was released on the stable version of Rust.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Async functions in Rust desugar to plain functions that return values that implement the Future trait.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Currently they are implemented with a finite-state machine.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Swift 5.5 (2021) added support for async/await as described in SE-0296.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] The async/await pattern is especially attractive to language designers of languages that do not have or control their own runtime, as async/await can be implemented solely as a transformation to a state machine in the compiler.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Supporters claim that asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written with async/await that looks almost like traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] In particular, it has been argued that await is the best way of writing asynchronous code in message-passing programs; in particular, being close to blocking code, readability and the minimal amount of boilerplate code were cited as await benefits.
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Critics of async/await note that the pattern tends to cause surrounding code to be asynchronous too; and that its contagious nature splits languages' library ecosystems between synchronous and asynchronous libraries and APIs, an issue often referred to as "function coloring".
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Alternatives to async/await that do not suffer from this issue are called "colorless".
[src:tower-middleware/async-await] Examples of colorless designs include Go's goroutines and Java's virtual threads.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] Tower is a library of modular and reusable components for building robust networking clients and servers.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] Tower provides a simple core abstraction, the `Service` trait, which represents an asynchronous function taking a request and returning either a response or an error.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] This abstraction can be used to model both clients and servers.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] Generic components, like `timeout`, rate limiting, and load balancing, can be modeled as `Service`s that wrap some inner service and apply additional behavior before or after the inner service is called.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] This allows implementing these components in a protocol-agnostic, composable way.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] Typically, such services are referred to as *middleware*.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] An additional abstraction, the `Layer` trait, is used to compose middleware with `Service`s.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] If a `Service` can be thought of as an asynchronous function from a request type to a response type, a `Layer` is a function taking a `Service` of one type and returning a `Service` of a different type.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] The `ServiceBuilder` type is used to add middleware to a service by composing it with multiple `Layer`s.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] Since the `Service` and `Layer` traits are important integration points for all libraries using Tower, they are kept as stable as possible, and breaking changes are made rarely.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] Therefore, they are defined in separate crates, `tower-service` and `tower-layer`.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] This crate contains re-exports of those core traits, implementations of commonly-used middleware, and utilities for working with `Service`s and `Layer`s.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] Finally, the `tower-test` crate provides tools for testing programs using Tower.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] Tower provides an abstraction layer, and generic implementations of various middleware.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] This means that the `tower` crate on its own does *not* provide a working implementation of a network client or server.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] Instead, Tower’s `Service` trait provides an integration point between application code, libraries providing middleware implementations, and libraries that implement servers and/or clients for various network protocols.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] A number of third-party libraries support Tower and the `Service` trait.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] If you’re the maintainer of a crate that supports Tower, we’d love to add your crate to this list!
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] Please open a PR adding a brief description of your library!
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] If you’re brand new to Tower and want to start with the basics, we recommend you check out some of our guides.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] The various middleware implementations provided by this crate are feature flagged, so that users can only compile the parts of Tower they need.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] By default, all the optional middleware are disabled.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] Alternatively, you can only enable some features.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] See here for a complete list of all middleware provided by Tower.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] Tower will keep a rolling MSRV (minimum supported Rust version) policy of **at least** 6 months.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] When increasing the MSRV, the new Rust version must have been released at least six months ago.
