[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] Various utility types and functions that are generally used with Tower.
[src:tower-middleware/latest-tower] , transforming either the request or the response.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] In computing, **load balancing** is the process of distributing a set of tasks over a set of resources (computing units) with the aim of making their overall processing more efficient.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can optimize response time and avoid unevenly overloading some compute nodes while other compute nodes are left idle.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is the subject of research in the field of parallel computers.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Two main approaches exist: static algorithms, which do not take into account the state of the different machines, and dynamic algorithms, which are usually more general and more efficient but require exchanges of information between the different computing units, at the risk of a loss of efficiency.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] A load-balancing algorithm always tries to answer a specific problem.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Among other things, the nature of the tasks, the algorithmic complexity, the hardware architecture on which the algorithms will run as well as required error tolerance, must be taken into account.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Therefore compromise must be found to best meet application-specific requirements.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of load balancing algorithms critically depends on the nature of the tasks.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the more information about the tasks is available at the time of decision making, the greater the potential for optimization.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Perfect knowledge of the execution time of each of the tasks allows to reach an optimal load distribution (see algorithm of prefix sum).
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Unfortunately, this is in fact an idealized case.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Knowing the exact execution time of each task is an extremely rare situation.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] For this reason, there are several techniques to get an idea of the different execution times.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] First of all, when tasks are relatively homogeneous size, it is possible to consider that each of them will require approximately the average execution time.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the execution time is considerably irregular, other techniques may be used.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] One technique is to add some metadata to each task.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Depending on the previous execution time for similar metadata, it is possible to make inferences for a future task based on statistics.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] In some cases, tasks depend on each other.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] These interdependencies can be illustrated by a directed acyclic graph.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Intuitively, some tasks cannot begin until others are completed.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Assuming that the required time for each of the tasks is known in advance, an optimal execution order must lead to the minimization of the total execution time.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] However, this is an NP-hard problem and therefore can be difficult to solve exactly.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] There are algorithms, like job scheduler, that calculate optimal task distributions using metaheuristic methods.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Another feature of the tasks critical for the design of a load balancing algorithm is their ability to be broken down into subtasks during execution.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The *tree-shaped computation* algorithm presented later takes great advantage of this specificity.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm is "static" when it does not take into account the state of the system for the distribution of tasks.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Thereby, the system state includes measures such as the load level (and sometimes even overload) of certain processors.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Instead, assumptions about the overall system are made beforehand, such as the arrival times and resource requirements of incoming tasks.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] In addition, the number of processors, their respective power and communication speeds are known.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, static load balancing aims to associate a known set of tasks with the available processors in order to minimize a certain performance function.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The key design choice is the performance function.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing techniques are commonly centralized around a router, or master, which distributes the loads and optimizes the performance function.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This minimization can take into account information related to the tasks to be distributed, and derive an expected execution time.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The advantage of static algorithms is that they are easy to set up and can efficient in the case of fairly regular tasks (such as processing HTTP requests from a website).
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] However, there is still some statistical variance in the assignment of tasks which can lead to the overloading of some computing units.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Unlike static load distribution algorithms, dynamic algorithms take into account the current load of each of the computing units (also called nodes) in the system.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] In this approach, tasks can be moved dynamically from an overloaded node to an underloaded node in order to receive faster processing.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] While these algorithms are much more complicated to design, they can improve performance, in particular, when the execution time varies greatly from one task to another.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing architecture can be more modular since it is not mandatory to have a specific node dedicated to the distribution of work.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] When tasks are uniquely assigned to a processor according to their state at a given moment, it is a unique assignment.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the tasks can be permanently redistributed according to the state of the system and its evolution, this is called dynamic assignment.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm that requires too much communication in order to reach its decisions runs the risk of slowing down the resolution of the overall problem.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Parallel computing infrastructures are often composed of units of different computing power, which should be taken into account for the load distribution.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] For example, lower-powered units may receive requests that require a smaller amount of computation, or, in the case of homogeneous or unknown request sizes, receive fewer requests than larger units.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] For shared-memory computers, managing write conflicts greatly slows down the speed of individual execution of each computing unit.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] However, they can work perfectly well in parallel.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Conversely, in the case of message exchange, each of the processors can work at full speed.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, when it comes to collective message exchange, all processors are forced to wait for the slowest processors to start the communication phase.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] In reality, few systems fall into exactly one of the categories.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] In general, the processors each have an internal memory to store the data needed for the next calculations and are organized in successive clusters.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Often, these processing elements are then coordinated through distributed memory and message passing.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the load balancing algorithm should be uniquely adapted to a parallel architecture.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Otherwise, there is a risk that the efficiency of parallel problem solving will be greatly reduced.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Adapting to the hardware structures seen above, there are two main categories of load balancing algorithms.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] On the one hand, the one where tasks are assigned by “master” and executed by “workers” who keep the master informed of the progress of their work, and the master can then take charge of assigning or reassigning the workload in case of the dynamic algorithm.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The literature refers to this as master-worker architecture.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, the control can be distributed between the different nodes.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The load balancing algorithm is then executed on each of them and the responsibility for assigning tasks (as well as re-assigning and splitting as appropriate) is shared.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The last category assumes a dynamic load balancing algorithm.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Since the design of each load balancing algorithm is unique, the previous distinction must be qualified.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Thus, it is also possible to have an intermediate strategy, with, for example, "master" nodes for each sub-cluster, which are themselves subject to a global "master".
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] There are also multi-level organizations, with an alternation between master-slave and distributed control strategies.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The latter strategies quickly become complex and are rarely encountered.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Designers prefer algorithms that are easier to control.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] In the context of algorithms that run over the very long term (servers, cloud...), the computer architecture evolves over time.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] However, it is preferable not to have to design a new algorithm each time.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] One parameter of a load balancing algorithm is therefore its ability to adapt to scalable hardware architecture.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This is called the scalability of the algorithm.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] An algorithm is called scalable for an input parameter when its performance remains relatively independent of the size of that parameter.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] When the algorithm is capable of adapting to a varying number of computing units, but the number of computing units must be fixed before execution, it is called moldable.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the algorithm is capable of dealing with a fluctuating amount of processors during its execution, the algorithm is said to be malleable.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancing algorithms are at least moldable.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Especially in large-scale computing clusters, it is not tolerable to execute a parallel algorithm that cannot withstand the failure of one single component.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, fault tolerant algorithms are being developed which can detect outages of processors and recover the computation.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] If the tasks are independent of each other, and if their respective execution time and the tasks can be subdivided, an optimal optimal algorithm is available under these assumptions.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] By dividing the tasks in such a way as to give the same amount of computation to each processor, all that remains to be done is to group the results together.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Using a prefix sum algorithm, this division can be calculated in logarithmic time with respect to the number of processors.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Most of the time, the execution time of a task is unknown and only rough approximations are available.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm may be efficient under these assumptions, but is less applicable when task durations are unknown.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Even if the execution time is not known in advance at all, static load distribution is always possible.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] In a round-robin algorithm, the first request is sent to the first server, then the next to the second, and so on down to the last.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Then it is started again, assigning the next request to the first server, and so on.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm can be weighted such that the most powerful units receive the largest number of requests and receive them first.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Randomized static load balancing is simply a matter of randomly assigning tasks to the different servers.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the number of tasks is known in advance, it is even more efficient to calculate a random permutation in advance.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This avoids communication costs for each assignment.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] There is no longer a need for a distribution master because every processor knows what task is assigned to it.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Even if the number of tasks is unknown, it is still possible to avoid communication with a pseudo-random assignment generation known to all processors.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The performance of this strategy (measured in total execution time for a given fixed set of tasks) decreases with the maximum size of the tasks.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Master-worker schemes are among the simplest dynamic load balancing algorithms.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] A master distributes the workload to all workers (also sometimes referred to as "slaves").
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Initially, all workers are idle and report this to the master.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The master answers worker requests and distributes the tasks to them.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] When he has no more tasks to give, he informs the workers so that they stop asking for tasks.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This scheme can distribute work evenly when assignment overhead is low.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Without taking into account the time needed for the assignment, the execution time would be comparable to the prefix sum seen above.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The problem with this algorithm is that it has difficulty adapting to a large number of processors because of the high amount of necessary communications.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This lack of scalability makes it quickly inoperable in very large servers or very large parallel computers.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] However, the quality of the algorithm can be greatly improved by replacing the master with a task list that can be used by different processors.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Although this algorithm can be said to be slightly more difficult to implement, it can improve scalability, although still insufficient for very large computing centers.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Another technique to overcome scalability problems when the time needed for task completion is unknown is work stealing.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The approach consists of assigning to each processor a certain number of tasks in a random or predefined manner, then allowing inactive processors to "steal" work from active or overloaded processors.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Several implementations of this concept exist, defined by a task division model and by the rules determining the exchange between processors.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] While this technique can be particularly effective, it is difficult to implement because it is necessary to ensure that communication does not become the primary occupation of the processors instead of solving the problem.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] In the case of atomic tasks, two main strategies can be distinguished, those where the processors with low load offer their computing capacity to those with the highest load, and those were the most loaded units wish to lighten the workload assigned to them.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] It has been shown that when the network is heavily loaded, it is more efficient for the least loaded units to offer their availability and when the network is lightly loaded, it is the overloaded processors that require support from the most inactive ones.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This rule of thumb limits the number of exchanged messages.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] In the case where one starts from a single large task that cannot be divided beyond an atomic level, a "Tree-Shaped computation" algorithm can be used, where the parent task is distributed in a work tree.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Initially, many processors have an empty task, except one that works sequentially on it.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Idle processors issue requests randomly to other processors (not necessarily active).
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] If the latter is able to subdivide the task it is working on, it does so by sending part of its work to the node making the request.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] It is then necessary to send a termination signal to the parent processor when the subtask is completed so that it, in turn, sends the message to its parent until it reaches the root of the tree.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] When the first processor, i.e. the root, has finished, a global termination message can be broadcast.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] In the end, it is necessary to assemble the results by going back up the tree.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of such an algorithm is close to the prefix sum when the job cutting and communication time is not too high compared to the work to be done.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] To avoid too high communication costs, it is possible to imagine a list of jobs on shared memory.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, a request is simply reading from a certain position on this shared memory at the request of the master processor.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] In addition to efficient problem solving through parallel computations, load balancing algorithms are widely used in HTTP request management where a site with a large audience must be able to handle a large number of requests per second.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] One of the most commonly used applications of load balancing is to provide a single Internet service from multiple servers, sometimes known as a server farm.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Commonly load-balanced systems include popular web sites, large Internet Relay Chat networks, high-bandwidth File Transfer Protocol (FTP) sites, Network News Transfer Protocol (NNTP) servers, Domain Name System (DNS) servers, and databases.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Round-robin DNS is an alternate method of load balancing that does not require a dedicated software or hardware node.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] In this technique, multiple IP addresses are associated with a single domain name; clients are given IP in a round-robin fashion.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] IP is assigned to clients with a short expiration so the client is more likely to use a different IP the next time they access the Internet service being requested.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Another more effective technique for load-balancing using DNS is to delegate www.example.org as a sub-domain whose zone is served by each of the same servers that are serving the website.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This technique works particularly well where individual servers are spread geographically on the Internet.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] However, the zone file for www.example.org on each server is different such that each server resolves its own IP Address as the A-record.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This way, when a server is down, its DNS will not respond and the web service does not receive any traffic.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] If the line to one server is congested, the unreliability of DNS ensures less HTTP traffic reaches that server.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Furthermore, the quickest DNS response to the resolver is nearly always the one from the network's closest server, ensuring geo-sensitive load-balancing .
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] A short TTL on the A-record helps to ensure traffic is quickly diverted when a server goes down.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Consideration must be given to the possibility that this technique may cause individual clients to switch between individual servers in mid-session.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Another approach to load balancing is to deliver a list of server IPs to the client, and then to have the client randomly select the IP from the list on each connection.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This essentially relies on all clients generating similar loads, and the law of large numbers to achieve a reasonably flat load distribution across servers.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] With this approach, the method of delivery of a list of IPs to the client can vary and may be implemented as a DNS list (delivered to all the clients without any round-robin), or via hardcoding it to the list.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] If a "smart client" is used, detecting that a randomly selected server is down and connecting randomly again, it also provides fault tolerance.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] For Internet services, a server-side load balancer is usually a software program that is listening on the port where external clients connect to access services.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer forwards requests to one of the "backend" servers, which usually replies to the load balancer.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This allows the load balancer to reply to the client without the client ever knowing about the internal separation of functions.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] It also prevents clients from contacting back-end servers directly, which may have security benefits by hiding the structure of the internal network and preventing attacks on the kernel's network stack or unrelated services running on other ports.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancers provide a mechanism for doing something special in the event that all backend servers are unavailable.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This might include forwarding to a backup load balancer or displaying a message regarding the outage.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] It is also important that the load balancer itself does not become a single point of failure.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Usually, load balancers are implemented in high-availability pairs which may also replicate session persistence data if required by the specific application.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Certain applications are programmed with immunity to this problem, by offsetting the load balancing point over differential sharing platforms beyond the defined network.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The sequential algorithms paired to these functions are defined by flexible parameters unique to the specific database.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Numerous scheduling algorithms, also called load-balancing methods, are used by load balancers to determine which back-end server to send a request to.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Simple algorithms include random choice, round robin, or least connections.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] An important issue when operating a load-balanced service is how to handle information that must be kept across the multiple requests in a user's session.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] If this information is stored locally on one backend server, then subsequent requests going to different backend servers would not be able to find it.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This might be cached information that can be recomputed, in which case load-balancing a request to a different backend server just introduces a performance issue.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Ideally, the cluster of servers behind the load balancer should not be session-aware, so that if a client connects to any backend server at any time the user experience is unaffected.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This is usually achieved with a shared database or an in-memory session database like Memcached.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] One basic solution to the session data issue is to send all requests in a user session consistently to the same backend server.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This is known as "persistence" or "stickiness".
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] A significant downside to this technique is its lack of automatic failover: if a backend server goes down, its per-session information becomes inaccessible, and any sessions depending on it are lost.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The same problem is usually relevant to central database servers; even if web servers are "stateless" and not "sticky", the central database is (see below).
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Assignment to a particular server might be based on a username, client IP address, or random.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Because of changes in the client's perceived address resulting from DHCP, network address translation, and web proxies this method may be unreliable.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Random assignments must be remembered by the load balancer, which creates a burden on storage.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] If the load balancer is replaced or fails, this information may be lost, and assignments may need to be deleted after a timeout period or during periods of high load to avoid exceeding the space available for the assignment table.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The random assignment method also requires that clients maintain some state, which can be a problem, for example when a web browser has disabled the storage of cookies.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Sophisticated load balancers use multiple persistence techniques to avoid some of the shortcomings of any one method.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Another solution is to keep the per-session data in a database.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This can reduce performance because it increases the load on the database: the database is best used to store information less transient than per-session data.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] To prevent a database from becoming a single point of failure, and to improve scalability, the database is often replicated across multiple machines, and load balancing is used to spread the query load across those replicas.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Microsoft's ASP.net State Server technology is an example of a session database.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] All servers in a web farm store their session data on State Server and any server in the farm can retrieve the data.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] When the client is a web browser, one approach is to store the per-session data in the browser itself.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] One way to achieve this is to use a browser cookie, suitably time-stamped and encrypted.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Storing session data on the client is generally the preferred solution: then the load balancer is free to pick any backend server to handle a request.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] However, this method of state-data handling may be unsuitable for some complex business logic scenarios, where the session state payload is large and recomputing it with every request on a server is not feasible.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] URL rewriting has major security issues because the end-user can easily alter the submitted URL and thus change session streams.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Yet another solution to storing persistent data is to associate a name with each block of data, and use a distributed hash table to pseudo-randomly assign that name to one of the available servers, and then store that block of data in the assigned server.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Hardware and software load balancers may have a variety of special features.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The fundamental feature of a load balancer is to be able to distribute incoming requests over a number of backend servers in the cluster according to a scheduling algorithm.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] A ratio can be manually assigned to cause some backend servers to get a greater share of the workload than others.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This is sometimes used as a simple way to account for some servers having more capacity than others, though it may not always work as desired.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] When the number of available servers drops below a certain number, or the load gets too high, standby servers can be brought online.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] request can become a major part of the demand on the Web Server's CPU; as the demand increases, users will see slower response times, as the TLS overhead is distributed among Web servers.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] To remove this demand on Web servers, a balancer can terminate TLS connections, passing HTTPS requests as HTTP requests to the Web servers.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] If the balancer itself is not overloaded, this does not noticeably degrade the performance perceived by end-users.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The downside of this approach is that all of the TLS processing is concentrated on a single device (the balancer) which can become a new bottleneck.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancer appliances include specialized hardware to process TLS.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Instead of upgrading the load balancer, which is quite expensive dedicated hardware, it may be cheaper to forgo TLS offload and add a few web servers.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Also, some server vendors such as Oracle/Sun now incorporate cryptographic acceleration hardware into their CPUs such as the T2000.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] F5 Networks incorporates a dedicated TLS acceleration hardware card in their local traffic manager (LTM) which is used for encrypting and decrypting TLS traffic.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] One clear benefit to TLS offloading in the balancer is that it enables it to do balancing or content switching based on data in the HTTPS request.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] attacks and generally offload work from the servers to a more efficient platform.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] compression available in all modern web browsers.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The larger the response and the further away the client is, the more this feature can improve response times.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The trade-off is that this feature puts additional CPU demand on the load balancer and could be done by web servers instead.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Different vendors use different terms for this, but the idea is that normally each HTTP request from each client is a different TCP connection.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This feature utilises HTTP/1.1 to consolidate multiple HTTP requests from multiple clients into a single TCP socket to the back-end servers.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer can buffer responses from the server and spoon-feed the data out to slow clients, allowing the webserver to free a thread for other tasks faster than it would if it had to send the entire request to the client directly.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] An option for asymmetrical load distribution, where request and reply have different network paths.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The balancer polls servers for application layer health and removes failed servers from the pool.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The balancer stores static content so that some requests can be handled without contacting the servers.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can arbitrarily modify traffic on the way through.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can hide HTTP error pages, remove server identification headers from HTTP responses, and encrypt cookies so that end users cannot manipulate them.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] , the ability to give different priorities to different traffic.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancers can send requests to different servers based on the URL being requested, assuming the request is not encrypted (HTTP) or if it is encrypted (via HTTPS) that the HTTPS request is terminated (decrypted) at the load balancer.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Authenticate users against a variety of authentication sources before allowing them access to a website.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] At least one balancer allows the use of a scripting language to allow custom balancing methods, arbitrary traffic manipulations, and more.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Firewalls can prevent direct connections to backend servers, for network security reasons.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Intrusion prevention systems offer application layer security in addition to the network/transport layer offered by firewall security.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can be useful in applications with redundant communications links.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] For example, a company may have multiple Internet connections ensuring network access if one of the connections fails.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] A failover arrangement would mean that one link is designated for normal use, while the second link is used only if the primary link fails.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Using load balancing, both links can be in use all the time.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] A device or program monitors the availability of all links and selects the path for sending packets.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The use of multiple links simultaneously increases the available bandwidth.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) facilitates an Ethernet to have an arbitrary topology, and enables per flow pair-wise load splitting by way of Dijkstra's algorithm, without configuration and user intervention.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The catalyst for TRILL was an event at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center which began on 13 November 2002.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The concept of Rbridges [sic] was first proposed to the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers in the year 2004, whom in 2005 rejected what came to be known as TRILL, and in the years 2006 through 2012 devised an incompatible variation known as Shortest Path Bridging.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The IEEE approved the IEEE 802.1aq standard in May 2012, also known as Shortest Path Bridging (SPB).
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] SPB allows all links to be active through multiple equal-cost paths, provides faster convergence times to reduce downtime, and simplifies the use of load balancing in mesh network topologies (partially connected and/or fully connected) by allowing traffic to load share across all paths of a network.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] SPB is designed to reduce configuration errors and preserves the plug-and-play nature that established Ethernet as the de facto protocol at Layer 2.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Many telecommunications companies have multiple routes through their networks or to external networks.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] They use sophisticated load balancing to shift traffic from one path to another to avoid network congestion on any particular link, and sometimes to minimize the cost of transit across external networks or improve network reliability.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Another way of using load balancing is in network monitoring activities.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Load balancers can be used to split huge data flows into several sub-flows and use several network analyzers, each reading a part of the original data.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This can be used for monitoring fast networks like 10GbE or STM64, where complex processing of the data may not be possible at wire speed.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is widely used in data center networks to distribute traffic across many existing paths between any two servers.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] It allows more efficient use of network bandwidth and reduces provisioning costs.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] In general, load balancing in datacenter networks can be classified as either static or dynamic.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing distributes traffic by computing a hash of the source and destination addresses and port numbers of traffic flows and using it to determine how flows are assigned to one of the existing paths.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing assigns traffic flows to paths by monitoring bandwidth use on different paths.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic assignments can also be proactive or reactive.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] In the former case, the assignment is fixed once made, while in the latter the network logic keeps monitoring available paths and shifts flows across them as network utilization changes (with arrival of new flows or completion of existing ones).
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] A comprehensive overview of load balancing in datacenter networks has been made available.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is often used to implement failover—the continuation of service after the failure of one or more of its components.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] The components are monitored continually (e.g., web servers may be monitored by fetching known pages), and when one becomes unresponsive, the load balancer is informed and no longer sends traffic to it.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] When a component comes back online, the load balancer starts rerouting traffic to it.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] For this to work, there must be at least one component in excess of the service's capacity (N+1 redundancy).
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This can be much less expensive and more flexible than failover approaches where every single live component is paired with a single backup component that takes over in the event of a failure (dual modular redundancy).
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Some RAID systems can also utilize hot spare for a similar effect.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] This technique can increase fault tolerance by enabling quick substitutions for the most complicated, most failure-prone parts of a system.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] However, it can make the load balancer itself a single point of failure.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] To maintain the necessary high throughput and low latency, organizations commonly deploy load balancing tools capable of advanced TCP optimizations, connection pooling, and adaptive scheduling.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] Such features help distribute incoming data requests evenly across servers or nodes, prevent congestion, and ensure that compute resources remain efficiently utilized.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] When deployed in large-scale or high-performance AI environments, load balancers also mitigate bandwidth constraints and accommodate varying data governance requirements—particularly when sensitive training data cannot be sent to third-party cloud services.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] By routing data locally (on-premises) or across private clouds, load balancers allow AI workflows to avoid public-cloud bandwidth limits, reduce transit costs, and maintain compliance with regulatory standards.
[src:tower-middleware/load-balancing-computing] As AI models expand in size (often measured by billions or even trillions of parameters), load balancing for data ingestion has grown in importance for maintaining the reliability, scalability, and cost efficiency of AI factories.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware often enables interoperability between applications that run on different operating systems, by supplying services so the application can exchange data in a standards-based way.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware sits "in the middle" between application software that may be working on different operating systems.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] It is similar to the middle layer of a three-tier single system architecture, except that it is stretched across multiple systems or applications.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Examples include EAI software, telecommunications software, transaction monitors, and messaging-and-queueing software.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] The distinction between operating system and middleware functionality is, to some extent, arbitrary.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] While core kernel functionality can only be provided by the operating system itself, some functionality previously provided by separately sold middleware is now integrated in operating systems.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] A typical example is the TCP/IP stack for telecommunications, nowadays included virtually in every operating system.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware is defined as software that provides a link between separate software applications.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] It is sometimes referred to as plumbing because it connects two applications and passes data between them.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware allows data contained in one database to be accessed through another.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] This makes it particularly useful for enterprise application integration and data integration tasks.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware gained popularity in the 1980s as a solution to the problem of how to link newer applications to older legacy systems, although the term had been in use since 1968.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] It also facilitated distributed processing, the connection of multiple applications to create a larger application, usually over a network.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] when compared to the operating system and network services.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware offers some unique technological advantages for business and industry.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] For example, traditional database systems are usually deployed in closed environments where users access the system only via a restricted network or intranet (e.g., an enterprise’s internal network).
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] With the phenomenal growth of the World Wide Web, users can access virtually any database for which they have proper access rights from anywhere in the world.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware addresses the problem of varying levels of interoperability among different database structures.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware facilitates transparent access to legacy database management systems (DBMSs) or applications via a web server without regard to database-specific characteristics.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Businesses frequently use middleware applications to link information from departmental databases, such as payroll, sales, and accounting, or databases housed in multiple geographic locations.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] In the highly competitive healthcare community, laboratories make extensive use of middleware applications for data mining, laboratory information system (LIS) backup, and to combine systems during hospital mergers.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware helps bridge the gap between separate LISs in a newly formed healthcare network following a hospital buyout.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware can help software developers avoid having to write application programming interfaces (API) for every control program, by serving as an independent programming interface for their applications.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] For Future Internet network operation through traffic monitoring in multi-domain scenarios, using mediator tools (middleware) is a powerful help since they allow operators, searchers and service providers to supervise Quality of service and analyse eventual failures in telecommunication services.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Finally, e-commerce uses middleware to assist in handling rapid and secure transactions over many different types of computer environments.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] In short, middleware has become a critical element across a broad range of industries, thanks to its ability to bring together resources across dissimilar networks or computing platforms.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] In 2004 members of the European Broadcasting Union (EBU) carried out a study of Middleware with respect to system integration in broadcast environments.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] This involved system design engineering experts from 10 major European broadcasters working over a 12-month period to understand the effect of predominantly software-based products to media production and broadcasting system design techniques.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] The resulting reports Tech 3300 and Tech 3300s were published and are freely available from the EBU web site.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Message-oriented middleware (MOM) is middleware where transactions or event notifications are delivered between disparate systems or components by way of messages, often via an enterprise messaging system.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] With MOM, messages sent to the client are collected and stored until they are acted upon, while the client continues with other processing.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] software may queue, duplicate, translate and deliver messages to disparate systems or components in a messaging system.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Intelligent Middleware (IMW) provides real-time intelligence and event management through intelligent agents.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] The IMW manages the real-time processing of high volume sensor signals and turns these signals into intelligent and actionable business information.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] The actionable information is then delivered in end-user power dashboards to individual users or is pushed to systems within or outside the enterprise.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] It is able to support various heterogeneous types of hardware and software and provides an API for interfacing with external systems.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] It should have a highly scalable, distributed architecture which embeds intelligence throughout the network to transform raw data systematically into actionable and relevant knowledge.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] It can also be packaged with tools to view and manage operations and build advanced network applications most effectively.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Content-centric middleware offers a simple *provider-consumer* abstraction through which applications can issue requests for uniquely identified content, without worrying about where or how it is obtained.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Juno is one example, which allows applications to generate content requests associated with high-level delivery requirements.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] The middleware then adapts the underlying delivery to access the content from sources that are best suited to matching the requirements.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] This is therefore similar to Publish/subscribe middleware, as well as the Content-centric networking paradigm.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] middleware enables a client to use services running on remote systems.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] middleware, it is possible for applications to send objects and request services in an object-oriented system.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] is middleware between applications and database servers.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] integration interface that operates between embedded applications, the embedded operating system, and external applications.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Policy appliance is a generic term referring to any form of middleware that manages policy rules.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] They can mediate between data owners or producers, data aggregators, and data users.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Among heterogeneous institutional systems or networks they may be used to enforce, reconcile, and monitor agreed information management policies and laws across systems (or between jurisdictions) with divergent information policies or needs.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Policy appliances support policy-based information management processes by enabling rules-based processing, selective disclosure, and accountability and oversight.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] IBM, Red Hat, Oracle Corporation and Microsoft are some of the vendors that provide middleware software.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Vendors such as Axway, SAP, TIBCO, Informatica, Objective Interface Systems, Pervasive, ScaleOut Software and webMethods were specifically founded to provide more niche middleware solutions.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Groups such as the Apache Software Foundation, OpenSAF, the ObjectWeb Consortium (now OW2) and OASIS' AMQP encourage the development of open source middleware.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Microsoft .NET "Framework" architecture is essentially "Middleware" with typical middleware functions distributed between the various products, with most inter-computer interaction by industry standards, open APIs or RAND software licence.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] Solace provides middleware in purpose-built hardware for implementations that may experience scale.
[src:tower-middleware/middleware-distributed-applications] StormMQ provides Message Oriented Middleware as a service.
[src:tower-middleware/rate-limiting] In computer networks, **rate limiting** is used to control the rate of requests sent or received by a network interface controller.
[src:tower-middleware/rate-limiting] It can be used to prevent DoS attacks and limit web scraping.
[src:tower-middleware/rate-limiting] Research indicates flooding rates for one zombie machine are in excess of 20 HTTP GET requests per second, legitimate rates much less.
[src:tower-middleware/rate-limiting] Rate limiting should be used along with throttling pattern to minimize the number of throttling errors.
[src:tower-middleware/rate-limiting] Hardware appliances can limit the rate of requests on layer 4 or 5 of the OSI model.
[src:tower-middleware/rate-limiting] Rate limiting can be induced by the network protocol stack of the sender due to a received ECN-marked packet and also by the network scheduler of any router along the way.
[src:tower-middleware/rate-limiting] While a hardware appliance can limit the rate for a given range of IP-addresses on layer 4, it risks blocking a network with many users which are masked by NAT with a single IP address of an ISP.
[src:tower-middleware/rate-limiting] Deep packet inspection can be used to filter on the session layer but will effectively disarm encryption protocols like TLS and SSL between the appliance and the protocol server (i.e. web server).
[src:tower-middleware/rate-limiting] Protocol servers using a request / response model, such as FTP servers or typically Web servers may use a central in-memory key-value database, like Redis or Aerospike, for session management.
[src:tower-middleware/rate-limiting] A rate limiting algorithm is used to check if the user session (or IP address) has to be limited based on the information in the session cache.
[src:tower-middleware/rate-limiting] In case a client made too many requests within a given time frame, HTTP servers can respond with status code 429: Too Many Requests.
[src:tower-middleware/rate-limiting] However, in some cases (i.e. web servers) the session management and rate limiting algorithm should be built into the application (used for dynamic content) running on the web server, rather than the web server itself.
[src:tower-middleware/rate-limiting] When a protocol server or a network device notice that the configured request limit is reached, then it will offload new requests and not respond to them.
[src:tower-middleware/rate-limiting] Sometimes they may be added to a queue to be processed once the input rate reaches an acceptable level, but at peak times the request rate can even exceed the capacities of such queues and requests have to be thrown away.
[src:tower-middleware/rate-limiting] Data centers widely use rate limiting to control the share of resources given to different tenants and applications according to their service level agreement.
[src:tower-middleware/rate-limiting] A variety of rate limiting techniques are applied in data centers using software and hardware.
[src:tower-middleware/rate-limiting] Virtualized data centers may also apply rate limiting at the hypervisor layer.
[src:tower-middleware/rate-limiting] Two important performance metrics of rate limiters in data centers are resource footprint (memory and CPU usage) which determines scalability, and precision.
[src:tower-middleware/rate-limiting] There usually exists a trade-off, that is, higher precision can be achieved by dedicating more resources to the rate limiters.
[src:tower-middleware/rate-limiting] A considerable body of research with focus on improving performance of rate limiting in data centers.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:tower-middleware/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
